  year = {2007},
  volume = {37},
  number = {2},
  pages = {139--162},
  doi = {10.1177/0048393107299685},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Jacobs provides critical exposition of Shils's multifaceted
  theory of tradition, identifying four distinct perspectives: pragmatic
  (traditions as solutions to recurrent problems), Burkean (traditions embody
  accumulated wisdom), veridical (traditions transmit truth/reality), and
  evolutionist (traditions as survival-tested practices). Jacobs argues these
  perspectives are not fully integrated in Shils's work, creating tensions—
  especially between the pragmatic view (traditions as contingent solutions)
  and the veridical view (traditions as truth-bearing).

  RELEVANCE: Essential secondary literature for understanding Shils's complex
  position. Jacobs's analysis reveals how even the most comprehensive theory
  of tradition contains unresolved conceptual tensions. For the project, this
  matters because different perspectives on tradition imply different criteria
  for failure/degeneration: pragmatic view suggests traditions fail when they
  no longer solve problems; veridical view suggests they fail when they
  distort truth; Burkean view suggests they fail when connection to past
  wisdom is severed. The project's theory of tradition-breakdown must
  address these distinct failure modes.

  POSITION: Critical exposition of Shils revealing internal tensions in
  tradition theory; important secondary literature on foundational text.
  },
  keywords = {Shils, tradition-theory, critical-exposition, Medium}
}

@book{marmor2009social,
  author = {Marmor, Andrei},
  title = {Social Conventions: From Language to Law},
  year = {2009},
  publisher = {Princeton University Press},
  address = {Princeton, NJ},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Conventions are arbitrary behavioral regularities constituted
  by reasons for action that are both self-perpetuating and content-independent.
  Marmor distinguishes "shallow" conventions (Lewis-type coordination) from
  "deep" conventions (constitutive of practices like language, law). Deep
  conventions generate new reasons for action and cannot be easily changed
  by individual or even collective decision. Language is the paradigm case:
  linguistic conventions are arbitrary yet normatively binding, learned
  through participation rather than explicit agreement.

  RELEVANCE: Marmor's distinction between shallow and deep conventions is
  crucial for understanding traditions. If traditions are deep conventions,
  they possess normative force not reducible to coordination benefits, and
  their "arbitrariness" is compatible with their authority. This helps explain
  why traditions persist even when their original functions are unclear:
  they constitute practices we cannot easily exit. For tradition-breakdown,
  the question becomes: when do deep conventions lose their constitutive power?
  When participants no longer recognize them as authoritative, or when
  participation itself breaks down?

  POSITION: Extends Lewis's convention theory to "deep" conventions with
  constitutive rather than merely coordinative function; important for
  understanding tradition's normative force.
  },
  keywords = {Marmor, deep-conventions, constitutive-rules, High}
}

@book{searle1995construction,
  author = {Searle, John R.},
  title = {The Construction of Social Reality},
  year = {1995},
  publisher = {Free Press},
  address = {New York},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Social reality consists of institutional facts created by
  collective intentionality and constitutive rules of the form "X counts as Y
  in context C." Institutions are systems of such constitutive rules. Money,
  property, marriage, government all exemplify institutional facts: they exist
  only because we collectively accept them as existing and assign them
  status-functions. Collective intentionality (we-intentions) is primitive,
  not reducible to individual intentionality. Language is the fundamental
  social institution enabling all others.

  RELEVANCE: Searle provides the dominant analytical framework for social
  ontology of institutions. If traditions are social institutions (or contain
  institutional elements), they inherit this structure: collective acceptance
  creates institutional reality. However, Searle's account emphasizes synchronic
  structure (collective acceptance at t) while traditions essentially involve
  diachronic transmission. The project must examine: Are traditions institutions?
  Do they require special forms of collective intentionality oriented toward
  the past? How does collective acceptance of tradition differ from collective
  acceptance of current institutions? Searle rarely discusses tradition directly.

  POSITION: Foundational social ontology providing constitutive-rule analysis
  of institutional reality; paradigm for analyzing tradition as institution.
  },
  keywords = {Searle, social-ontology, institutional-facts, High}
}

@book{bicchieri2006grammar,
  author = {Bicchieri, Cristina},
  title = {The Grammar of Society: The Nature and Dynamics of Social Norms},
  year = {2006},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  address = {Cambridge},
  doi = {10.1017/CBO9780511616037},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Social norms are behavioral rules supported by empirical
  and normative expectations: people follow norm N if they believe (1) others
  follow N (empirical expectation), (2) others expect them to follow N and
  may sanction non-compliance (normative expectation), and (3) they prefer
  to follow N conditional on (1) and (2). This distinguishes social norms
  from conventions (lack normative force), moral rules (independent of
  others' expectations), and descriptive norms (mere regularities). Social
  norms are self-enforcing through mutual expectations rather than external
  enforcement.

  RELEVANCE: Bicchieri's framework helps distinguish traditions from norms
  and conventions. Are traditions social norms? Partly: they involve normative
  expectations and sanctions for non-compliance. But traditions seem to involve
  additional elements: connection to the past, transmission, and claims to
  authority based on antiquity rather than just mutual expectations. For
  tradition-breakdown, Bicchieri's analysis of how norms unravel (when
  expectations become misaligned) may illuminate how traditions fail: when
  transmission breaks down, empirical and normative expectations diverge,
  undermining the norm.

  POSITION: Game-theoretic and experimental approach to social norms;
  distinguishes norms from conventions and moral rules through expectation
  structure.
  },
  keywords = {Bicchieri, social-norms, normative-expectations, Medium}
}

@book{miller2010moral,
  author = {Miller, Seumas},
  title = {The Moral Foundations of Social Institutions: A Philosophical Study},
  year = {2010},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  address = {New York},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Social institutions are organizations or systems of
  organizations embodying collective ends pursued through joint activity
  according to constitutive and regulative rules. Institutions have both
  structure (roles, rules) and function (collective ends). Miller's teleological
  account emphasizes that institutions exist to serve collective ends—these
  ends provide both explanation and normative standard. Institutions require
  joint action (multiple agents acting interdependently toward shared goal)
  sustained across time through mechanisms ensuring coordination and
  perpetuation.

  RELEVANCE: Miller's teleological approach differs from Searle's constitutive-
  rule approach, emphasizing collective ends over collective acceptance. For
  traditions, this raises: Do traditions have collective ends? Or do they
  simply perpetuate practices whose original ends are lost? If traditions lack
  clear collective ends, Miller's framework may not apply. However, his
  emphasis on joint action sustained over time captures tradition's diachronic
  character better than Searle. For breakdown: traditions fail when collective
  ends become unclear or when joint action mechanisms fail to perpetuate
  the practice across generations.

  POSITION: Teleological account of social institutions emphasizing collective
  ends and joint action; alternative to Searle's constitutive-rule approach.
  },
  keywords = {Miller, social-institutions, teleological-account, Medium}
}

@incollection{gilbert1989social,
  author = {Gilbert, Margaret},
  title = {On Social Facts},
  year = {1989},
  publisher = {Routledge},
  address = {London},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Social phenomena require "plural subjects"—multiple persons
  constituting, by virtue of joint commitment, a single subject of attitudes
  and actions. Joint commitments create obligations among participants that
  individuals cannot unilaterally rescind. This differs from aggregate views
  (social facts = aggregated individual facts) and collective intentionality
