  maintaining and transmitting the practice, creating obligations to past and
  future participants. This explains tradition's normative force without appeal
  to inherent value—the force comes from joint commitment structure. For
  breakdown: traditions fail when joint commitments dissolve, when participants
  no longer recognize obligations to each other (past/future). However, Gilbert
  rarely discusses temporal extension or intergenerational joint commitments.

  POSITION: Plural subject theory of social phenomena emphasizing joint
  commitment and normative obligations among participants.
  },
  keywords = {Gilbert, plural-subject, joint-commitment, Medium}
}

@book{tuomela2002philosophy,
  author = {Tuomela, Raimo},
  title = {The Philosophy of Social Practices: A Collective Acceptance View},
  year = {2002},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  address = {Cambridge},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Social practices are systems of rule-governed activities
  based on collective acceptance. Collective acceptance (accepting something
  "as a group") creates social reality through we-mode thinking (distinct
  from mere I-mode aggregation). Practices are ontologically collective:
  they exist only when collectively accepted and maintained. Tuomela
  distinguishes constitutive and regulative social practices, emphasizes
  positional roles and deontic powers, and argues we-mode collective
  acceptance is necessary for full-blooded social practices.

  RELEVANCE: Tuomela's collective acceptance view, like Searle's, emphasizes
  synchronic structure. For traditions, the question is whether collective
  acceptance must be oriented toward the past or whether present collective
  acceptance suffices. If tradition requires accepting something "because it
  was handed down," this involves distinct intentional content from accepting
  something for current reasons. Tuomela's framework illuminates how practices
  are collectively maintained but may need supplementation to handle diachronic
  transmission. For breakdown: traditions fail when collective acceptance
  lapses or shifts from we-mode to I-mode.

  POSITION: Collective acceptance theory emphasizing we-mode versus I-mode
  collective intentionality; social practices exist through being collectively
  accepted.
  },
  keywords = {Tuomela, collective-acceptance, we-mode, Medium}
}

